    {
      "title": "Lām al-Amr and Lā al-Nāhiya",
      "titleArabic": "لام الأمر ولا الناهية",
      "content": [
        "Lām al-amr is used for commands in the third person (let him/them do), while lā al-nāhiya is used for prohibitions. Both cause jazm in the following verb."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Lām al-amr: لِيَذْهَبْ (let him go) - 3rd person command",
        "Lā al-nāhiya: لَا تَذْهَبْ (don't go) - prohibition",
        "Both cause jazm (jussive mood) in the verb",
        "Jazm can follow commands/prohibitions in response clauses"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "لِيَجْلِسْ", "english": "Let him sit (3rd person command)" },
        { "arabic": "لَا تَكْتُبْ", "english": "Don't write (prohibition)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Defective Verbs (الفعل الناقص)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل الناقص",
      "content": [
        "Defective verbs have wāw or yā' as their final radical. The weak letter undergoes various changes depending on the conjugation and the vowel preceding it."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Final radical is wāw or yā'",
        "Weak letter may appear as alif, wāw, yā', or drop entirely",
        "In jussive: لَمْ يَمْشِ, لَمْ يَدْعُ (weak letter drops)",
        "Common verbs: مَشَى, دَعَا, بَنَى, رَمَى, نَسِيَ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مَشَى - يَمْشِي - لَمْ يَمْشِ", "english": "to walk" },
        { "arabic": "دَعَا - يَدْعُو - لَمْ يَدْعُ", "english": "to call/invite" },
        { "arabic": "بَنَى - يَبْنِي - لَمْ يَبْنِ", "english": "to build" }
      ]
    }
  ],
